Suggestion from Balint:

I've looked at the example. I don't think it's an error, but you might want to add a sentence to clarify something.  

The confusion might arise from the enormous equivalence classes that the d2 metric generates in the space of Riemann integrable 
functions (superset of C[0,1]). 
If f and g are Riemann integrable on [0, 1] and f=g almost everywhere, then d2(f, g)=0.    

He is right that with the d2 metric the sequence {t^n} converges to f=0 (which is in C[0,1]), but in a d2 sense this
 limit is equivalent with other functions that are not in C[0,1]. The message still holds: the d2 metric does not make C[0,1] complete.  